<font color="#FF0000">FACES ON THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec 30 20:15:49 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
To Vietnam Vet,<br>
    Maya Lin's design was chosen at the conclusion of a very tough &quot;competition.&quot;  She won fair and square.  No flag, no statues, just a beautifully simple memorial to those who served and those who lost their lives.  I am sorry you did not read nor understand her quote on the Home Page.  <br>
    I don't know why you are so displeased with the memorial, especially considering all the praise it has received.  You got your flag.  You got your (stupid) statue which, thank god, is placed some distance away from The Wall.  <br>
    As for some of the things you say, I'm sorry, I disagree.  I guess those who look for ugliness (you may substitute &quot;hatred,&quot; &quot;bitterness,&quot; etc.)in the world find it, and those who look for beauty find it.  <br>
    Maya Lin's design is truly magnificent, a work of art that people will talk about WITH PRAISE for ages, a moving and fitting tribute to all those who served, and a reminder of the cost of war.<br>
    As for wishing to see faces, I fail to understand how you can gaze at the Memorial and not see faces, including your own (and mine).<br>
                         
<p><code>--   (Another Vietnam Vet) </code><p>


